ues, can best be understood as a reciprocal framing relation between the bodily means of communicating affect (by face and voice) and technologies of graphic reproduction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPoeticsxHistory. 0aSemiotics. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aCinema & Media Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAndy Warhol.  aEdgar Allan Poe.  aGertrude Stein.  aHenry James.  aMelanie Klein.  aSilvan Tomkins.  aWilfred Bion.  aaffect.  atelevision.  atheatricality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082326249640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823262496423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823262496/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK